In JavaScript, you can use the `localStorage` object to store data on the client-side. Here's an example of how to save data to and read it back from localStorage:

Firstly, let's define a key that we'll use to store our data:
```javascript
const storageKey = "myData";
```
Next, we can save some data to localStorage using the `setItem()` method:
```javascript
// Save some data to localStorage
const myData = { name: "John Doe", age: 30 };
localStorage.setItem(storageKey, JSON.stringify(myData)));
```
In this example, we're saving an object (`myData`) to localStorage using the `setItem()` method. We're also converting the data to a string format using the `JSON.stringify()` method.

Now, let's read back the data from localStorage using the `getItem()` method:
```javascript
// Read back the data from localStorage
const storedData = localStorage.getItem(storageKey);
if (storedData) {
  // Convert the data back to its original format
  const myData = JSON.parse(storedData);
  console.log("Retrieved data:", myData);
} else {
  console.log("No data found in localStorage with key:", storageKey);
}
```
In this example, we're reading back the data from localStorage using the `getItem()` method. We're also checking if any data was retrieved and converting it back to its original format using the `JSON.parse()` method.
